<TEXT>
the worlds beef trade is undergoing rapid 
changes as production declines in 1989 and production falters in 
some major countries 
one result the agriculture department said wednesday is that 
the united states is edging ahead of new zealand as a worldclass 
beef exporter 
us exports are estimated at 450000 metric tons up from 
313000 tons in 1988 the departments foreign agricultural service 
reported exports are expected to rise to about 508000 tons in 
1990 
most of the increase is the result of larger sales to japan 
under last years trade liberalization by tokyo to open the door to 
more beef and citrus 
new zealands total beef and veal exports meanwhile are 
estimated at 439000 tons in 1989 and 368000 tons in 1990 
production rose this year as drought forced more cattle to 
slaughter 
us imports of beef which reached 11 million tons in 1988 
are expected to decline this year to around 990000 tons the 
report said the decrease is the result of smaller shipments from 
australia where production is down and more meat was diverted to 
the lucrative japanese market 
the report said us beef imports in 1990 are likely to decline 
slightly to around 970000 tons as australia continues exporting 
to japan 
us beef exports grew at a faster rate than those of the 
other five countries during the 1980s rising from sixth to fourth 
position by 1988 the report said in 1989 it is expected that 
the united states will surpass new zealand to become the third 
largest beef exporter in the world 
the top six beef exporters in 1989 are australia 823000 tons 
the 12nation european economic community 759000 united states 
450000 new zealand 439000 brazil 370000 and argentina 
350000 
