<TEXT>
stung by electoral successes of the extreme right 
and fierce debate over rights for moslems the government has 
appointed a troubleshooter to formulate new policy for integrating 
immigrants into french society 
premier michel rocard on wednesday named hubert prevot as 
permanent secretary of a government committee that will grapple 
with what has become the leading issue in domestic politics 
the economic situation of france no longer permits us to be a 
land of immigration government spokesman louis le pensec said 
after the appointment was announced at the weekly cabinet meeting 
its now a question of integrating foreigners who have come to 
make their homes here and wish to live here permanently le 
pensec said 
prevot 61 will head a task force of 13 ministers to grapple 
with the issues of integrating moslems into the secular school 
system the definition of a political refugee illegal workers and 
immigrant housing 
the panel will submit conclusions to the government sometime 
after jan 31 
the creation of the task force represents a victory for the 
extremeright national front headed by jeanmarie le pen who has 
fulfilled a longheld goal of putting immigration high on the 
governments agenda 
it comes the same day mariefrance stirbois took the partys 
first seat in the national assembly since electoral reforms in 
1988 mrs stirbois won the seat for suburban dreux in a runoff 
election sunday 
immigration exploded into a frontpage issue in october after 
three girls with north african origins insisted on wearing islamic 
scarves to their junior high school 
french law dating to the turn of the century separates church 
and state all forms of proselytizing and wearing of religious 
symbols are prohibited in the secular school system 
though two of the girls removed their scarves and returned to 
class on saturday they ignited fresh debate over whether some 
immigrants can be absorbed into french culture 
le pen has pushed the issue for years arguing that social 
payments to immigrants cut into benefits for native french 
citizens his party fares well in areas like dreux that have a high 
population of noneuropean immigrants 
in an interview published in wednesdays edition of the 
conservative newspaper le figaro le pen urged the government to 
expel all foreigners who arrived in france after 1974 
le pen says a law passed that year that restricted immigration 
to political asylum or reuniting families is widely flouted 
wisdom would dictate reducing the number of foreigners in 
france and reversing the flood le pen was quoted as saying in 
