<TEXT>
the governments massive cholesterol education 
program places too much emphasis on drug treatments that may do 
more harm than good a congressional panel was told today 
but a federal official defended the national cholesterol 
education program saying its guidelines will improve the health of 
americans and reduce the risk of heart attacks the nations 
leading killer 
thomas j moore an investigative reporter whose article in the 
september issue of the atlantic magazine inflamed the controversy 
over cholesterol monitoring said he questions the value of what he 
says is aggressive treatment recommended by the federal program 
this is a very serious and expensive mistake in public 
policy he told the house energy and commerce subcommittee on 
health 
the programs cholesterol guidelines recommend diet as the 
treatment of choice but says that failing that patients with high 
levels of cholesterol should seek treatment with drugs 
an estimated 60 million americans are believed to have high 
blood cholesterol a fatty substance that can clog arteries and 
contribute to heart disease and heart attacks 
besides cholesterol other factors that have been identified as 
factors in heart disease are high blood pressure obesity smoking 
and lack of exercise 
moore said he agrees with advice in the programs guidelines 
that americans should have their cholesterol levels checked and 
make their diets healthier by eating less fat fewer calories and 
more fiber 
he also said there is evidence that high cholesterol levels in 
middleaged men makes them more vulnerable to heart disease 
although he said the evidence of a link is much weaker for men over 
65 and women of all ages who have no history of heart disease 
but the central question is do we have effective medical 
treatment that justifies putting 60 million people under longterm 
care of their doctor moore said 
he said the evidence he has found shows that diet does little to 
lower cholesterol levels in the blood and that while drug 
treatments show more benefit they have not demonstrated 
significant ability to ward off fatal heart attacks 
moore said his complaint with the cholesterol program of the 
national heart lung and blood institute is that with evidence that 
diet isnt a significant factor in lowering cholesterol levels 
many who follow the programs guidelines will turn to drug 
treatments that can have side effects including liver damage 
cataracts and digestive difficulties 
when people become frustrated with diet there will be an 
expansion of drug treatment beyond what the architects of the 
program expected he said 
claude lenfant director of the heart lung and blood institute 
part of the national institutes of health disputed moore and said 
clinical trials have shown that lowering cholesterol levels by diet 
or drugs decreases the incidence of heart disease 
most people with high blood cholesterol will be able to lower 
their levels with diet alone and only a small minority will have 
to resort to drugs he said 
lenfant also noted that when the first surgeon generals report 
on smoking and health was released in the mid 1960s critics 
started talking about the tobacco myth 
it has taken a long time for the ripples to subside and for 
near unanimity to emerge that the risks of smoking are no myth 
he said 
much the same is true for cholesterol it may take a while 
before there is universal agreement about cholesterollowering but 
cholesterol is also no myth 
