<TEXT>
the house armed services committee chairman 
charged thursday that the bush administration bungled the 
announcement of future cuts in defense spending by failing to spell 
out a military strategy 
rep les aspin dwis said defense secretary dick cheney 
directed the services to come up with ways to slash 180 billion 
from pentagon spending during fiscal 1992 to fiscal 1994 but 
provided no policy guidance 
without a strategy the administration faces the likelihood of 
the defense budget being crafted by lawmakers concerned with 
parochial interests instead of by the administration aspin said 
in the last couple of weeks the administration has fumbled the 
defense budget ball big time aspin said in a speech to the 
national security industrial association 
the wisconsin democrat said the budget exercise asked the 
services where they would cut it didnt tell them what threats to 
assume what roles to emphasize or what missions to minimize 
complicating the situation was cheneys decision to discuss the 
cuts in published reports and television interviews aspin said 
the cuts according to the lawmaker will come from unrealistic 
budget totals envisioned by the pentagon and in the long run will 
amount to substantial but no massive reductions 
if we compare it to the fiveyear defense plan that they are 
now working with in the pentagon a cut of 180 billion in 1992 
1993 and 1994 would mean a reduction of about 45 percent per year 
in each of those years thats in real terms after accounting for 
inflation aspin said 
the problems stemming from the administrations handling of the 
issue will be worse if it falters in producing a strategy for the 
budget cuts aspin said 
when your defense budget is not supported by a military 
strategy it will be patched together with a pork strategy aspin 
said of course even if you have a military strategy it is hard 
to fend off a pork strategy but if you have no military strategy 
you have no chance 
aspin said the administration faces allegations that it will be 
fashioning a strategy to fit the budget 
nevertheless the administration must reopen the debate over 
soviet military capabilities and intentions in a time of 
fastmoving events in eastern europe 
the administration then must outline a strategy to ensure that 
the united states gets the most for its reduced defense dollars 
aspin said 
