law 
deals that the hearing is focusing on are literally just the 
tip of the iceberg james p murphy an attorney for the treasury 
departments office of thrift supervision told us district court 
judge stanley sporkin 
under an arrangement approved by attorneys for both sides a 
sample of four deals two land transactions a taxsharing 
arrangement between lincoln and its holding company and a deal 
involving stock will occupy the two days of hearings that began 
thursday 
i assume you picked the worst ones sporkin a former chief 
enforcement officer for the securities and exchange commission 
said to murphy the judge ordered the hearing on the governments 
motion to dismiss keatings suit in what regulators say will end up 
as the costliest sampl collapse in history 
last may a month after regulators seized keatings irvine 
calif thrift he filed the suit seeking to nullify the 
governments action regulators contended the sampl had lost between 
1 billion and 25 billion in federally insured deposits through 
fraud risky investments and sham real estate transactions 
the government has summoned keating to appear as a witness 
the target of a federal grand jury investigation in los angeles 
keating invoked his fifth amendment right against 
selfincrimination and refused to answer questions in a subpoenaed 
appearance last month before the house banking committee 
in his suit keating and his attorneys allege that lincoln was 
being operated soundly met federal capital requirements and was 
making a profit and that its takeover by the government was 
capricious and arbitrary 
before hearing testimony sporkin denied efforts by keatings 
attorneys to quash as evidence four letters from one of lincolns 
attorneys prior to the takeover last april 14 
charles m stern a los angeles attorney representing keating 
said allowing the government to use the letters would violate his 
clients attorneyclient privilege we should not be forced to 
have our own lawyers used against us he said 
however attorneys for the thrift regulators said the letters 
effectively became government property once the government seized 
lincoln 
sporkin granted keatings request for government records dating 
back to 1985 on taxsharing agreements between hundreds of thrifts 
around the country and their holding companies 
a key element of the governments case is its contention that 
lincoln and its holding company american continental corp of 
phoenix abused a taxsharing agreement to effectively siphon off 
nearly 95 million in federally insured deposits 
keating is chairman of american continental which filed for a 
chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization one day before the government 
placed lincoln into conservatorship 
government regulators in 1986 had approved the taxsharing 
arrangement under which american was supposed to collect taxes 
from lincoln and forward the money to the internal revenue service 
but murphy said lincoln and american continental fraudulently 
misused the accord to effectively allow the holding company to use 
the tax collections as a nointerest loan from lincoln 
federal thrift regulations prohibit savings and loan 
institutions from lending money to their holding companies 
