<TEXT>
sixteen savings and loans were permitted to 
sell 3 billion in uninsured debt to their customers the same 
practice that cost many depositors at lincoln savings and loan 
association their life savings thrift regulators said thursday 
despite the lincoln debacle the office of thrift supervision 
this year allowed seven sampls to begin selling debt to retail 
customers and another nine institutions to continue sales approved 
earlier according to a twopage summary released by the office 
such sales are attracting heavy scrutiny because some 22000 
investors many of them elderly pensioners and widows lost an 
estimated 250 million by purchasing subordinated debt in american 
continental corp the parent company of the irvine califbased 
lincoln in 1987 and 1988 
in sometimes tearful testimony lincoln customers told the house 
banking committee last month they were misled into believing the 
debt certificates were federally insured 
the lincoln debt was sold in the branch offices of the sampl and 
offered in amounts as small as 1000 a feature that appealed to 
unsophisticated investors 
the thrift office said the approved debt sales in addition to 
lincoln totaled 3017 billion in some instances denominations as 
low as 1000 were offered 
thrift office rules required that sampls offering debt meet 
capital standards at the time of the approval however according 
to sheshunoff information services of austin texas two of the 16 
sampls as of june 30 had no tangible capital they are security first 
federal savings and loan assocation of daytona beach fla and 
centrust savings bank miami 
two others fall short of new standards effective thursday which 
require sampls to hold capital amounting to 15 percent of their 
assets the firm said they are cenlar federal savings bank 
princeton nj and tcf bank savings minneapolis 
centrust was allowed to offer 50 million in notes in minimum 
denominations of 2000 while cenlar was permitted 20 million in 
1000 denominations tcf and security first sold their debt in 
minimums of 10000 
however not all of the debt sales are suspect alex sheshunoff 
the owner of the information firm said the 1 billion offering in 
100000 minimums by world savings and loan association oakland 
calif considered one of the best sampls in the nation is probably 
an excellent investment 
sheshunoff said sampls should be permitted to offer their debt 
without going through an underwriter but he said they should 
screen out unsophisticated buyers by offering the debt in large 
denominations and should clearly disclose that the debt is 
uninsured 
