<TEXT>
some call it a catch22 snare zapped if they do and zapped 
if they dont thats the predicament claimed for some students at 
westside high school in omaha neb who want an offhours bible 
club 
the problem has surfaced at numerous public schools across the 
country 
federal courts have issued conflicting opinions about it and 
although congress has passed a special law allowing for such clubs 
the issue is now before the us supreme court 
several church groups supporting student rights to form such 
groups contend westside put a doublenix on it barring the club 
for lack of school sponsorship although such sponsorship would 
make the club unconstitutional 
either way its out according to the school boards position 
amounting to a selfimposed catch22 for the students the 
church groups say in a brief supporting the students appeal to the 
supreme court 
efforts at organizing such clubs strictly by student initiative 
and without official school involvement has had a rocky and 
litigious course in many communities throughout this decade 
trying to dispel the confusion congress adopted the equal 
access act in 1984 guaranteeing student religious groups the same 
rights to meet in offclass hours as other nonacademic 
extracurricular groups 
the law was based on rights of free speech that schools with a 
limited open forum allowing students to organize clubs about 
politics dancing archery bridge or whatever also must allow 
clubs that talk religion 
but schools have remained skittish about any religious inklings 
on campus ever since the 196263 high court decisions banning 
sponsored prayer or bible readings 
some educators have come to believe that all religious speech 
must be extirpated from the schools the churches brief says 
but such a view fails to distinguish between officially sponsored 
speech and individual rights 
congress sought to end discrimination against student religious 
speech but the brief says this case shows that at least some 
local school officials fundamentally reject each and every premise 
on which congress acted 
on the other hand the american jewish committee which opposes 
the act has filed a brief contending that to allow a school 
religious club would open the door to organized religious 
activities in public schools 
in a dispute at the wiliamport pa high school the supreme 
court in 1986 affirmed the right of students to meet for bible and 
prayer outside classtime but the case was decided on a technical 
point not generally applicable 
early this year a federal appeals court ruled against a student 
religious group at a renton wash high school giving the school 
discretion to allow clubs considered even remotely related to 
education but not if religious 
in the dispute at westside high school a federal district court 
upheld the school boards refusal to allow a religious club while 
permitting about 30 other other clubs such as for chess and scuba 
diving 
but a federal appeals court overturned that decision rejecting 
the schools position that the various clubs were 
curriculumrelated 
that claim the court said would allow a school administration 
simply to choose whatever clubs it wished for vague reasons but 
then to discriminate against particular student groups because 
of religious speech 
it would be tragic if the court allows a school board to 
eviscerate the equal acess act by declaring all clubs except 
relgious ones to be curriculumrelated says oliver thomas 
general counsel for the baptist joint committee on public affairs 
other groups joining in the brief were the christian legal 
scoiety the national association of evangelicals the presbyterian 
church usa and the church of jesus christ of latterday saints 
us catholic bishops have filed their own brief affirming 
rights of students to form voluntary bible clubs 
the brief says the action of the school officials instead of 
upholding the constitution have created a constitutional problem 
by inhibiting religious activity and conveying a message of 
disapproval of religious activity to both the students involved and 
the community at large 
oral arguments before the supreme court are expected to be heard 
this month or early next year with a decision by next summer 
meanwhile bridget megens who with friends initiated attempts 
for a bible club at westside high school in 1984 and is now married 
and the mother of a young daughter says i was afraid there 
might not be anybody to carry the torch 
however she says about 15 students still are pushing the 
effort there are even some kids who are not christians who are 
interested she told the monthly church and state 
she says she hopes the dispute will be resolved so her daughter 
can belong to a bible study group at her high school when she grows 
up 
</TEXT>
