<TEXT>
this is a summary of the disaster assistance act of 1988 and 
procedures farmers followed to collect aid 
the program originally was written to provide cash to farmers 
who suffered crop losses of more than 35 percent due to drought 
hail excessive moisture or related condition in 1988 
farmers who lost more than 65 percent of their normal harvest 
were required to protect themselves with federal crop insurance 
this year 
the bill covered all crops in all states not just drought 
areas as its regulations moved from the halls of congress to the 
county offices where the checks were written the list of weather 
conditions eligible for aid grew it eventually included 
depending on the individual county insects sandstorms fungus 
high winds and cold 
the bill required farmers to state their acreage whether it was 
irrigated andor insured the normal yield and the actual 
production on that acreage they also had to state the cause for 
their loss and in what manner the land had been farmed 
their applications for aid were approved or denied by 
threemember committees of locally elected farmers serving as the 
governments agents 
regulations require only 5 percent of aid applications to be 
verified for accurate information although many offices said they 
routinely checked 15 percent as with other farm payment programs 
paperwork remained at the county offices no regulation requires 
data on individual farms to be routinely forwarded to state or 
federal headquarters 
the relief act stated that payments were limited to 100000 per 
farmer and that no producer with gross revenues in excess of 2 
million was eligible for aid 
checks were written at the county office only county totals of 
aid not individual summaries were fed into national computers 
federal agriculture officials have not yet compiled figures on the 
amount of aid disbursed based on the crops damaged or on the 
specific weather problems cited for crop losses 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891207-0179 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the 1988 drought assistance bill for us 
farmers set a record for disaster programs totaling 39 billion 
in payments when all applications had been processed 
this year with the drought area reduced and the severity 
lessened congress tightened eligibility requirements and pulled 
the purse strings tighter authorizing less than 25 percent of the 
money released in 1988 
here are details of the two relief programs 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
congress authorized 39 billion in cash payments to farmers 
who could prove crop losses in 1988 the 1989 authorization is 897 
million 
both programs set a 100000 limit per producer on combined 
payments for crop losses and livestock relief 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
under each program an applicant could not have a gross annual 
income greater than 2 million 
growers had to absorb crop losses if they totaled less than 35 
percent of normal production the programs differed for losses 
above 35 percent 
the 1988 bill encompassed all crops from such program crops 
as corn wheat and cotton that the government supports with price 
subsidies to riskier crops like kiwi fruit or endive 
the 1989 bill pays on losses of 35 percent to 50 percent only 
for program crops farmers of nonprogram crops are paid only if 
losses totaled more than 50 percent of a normal harvest whether 
producers receive aid also depends on whether they participated in 
federal commodity programs and bought crop insurance 
the 1988 bill provided two tiers of payment farmers received 
65 percent of a preestablished payment rate based on such 
factors as market prices and subsidies for losses of 35 percent 
to 75 percent of normal production they got 90 percent of the 
payment rate if losses topped 75 percent 
in 1989 the highest payment for any loss was 65 percent of the 
payment rate 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
both programs required farmers with losses greater than 65 
percent to buy federal crop insurance the subsequent year each 
bill permitted some instances in which crop insurance could be 
waived 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the 1988 bill permitted farmers to receive aid on the early 
loss of crops such as winter wheat or cotton even if they 
replanted the same acres with different crops and had normal 
harvests 
to prevent such double dipping the 1989 law sharply reduced 
benefits to farmers who chose to plant replacement crops due to 
drought or other weather conditions critics said this penalized 
farmers who were simply trying to help themselves and the law was 
modified in october to be more generous 
as modified aid payments on damaged crops will be reduced only 
if the value of the replacement crop is more than half of the 
countys average yield and then only by the value above the 50 
percent threshold 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
both programs provided help for livestock producers expanding 
existing feed and water programs to relieve droughtrelated 
shortages for herds eligible livestock include cattle sheep 
goats swine poultry horses and mules and fish raised in 
commercial ponds 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

