<TEXT>
it was the great untold story of the 1980s or was it in the 
newspaper every day 
suddenly an unusual number of people in their prime were dying 
after a long illness their obituaries often said 
though frequently written with respect for personal or family 
wishes the vague death notices deflected early public attention 
from a toll that would mount to almost 70000 americans victims of 
a virus discovered only in 1983 that infected an estimated 6 
million to 8 million people worldwide by the end of the 80s 
halfway through the decade the death of movie star rock hudson 
personalized for many americans what had been a faceless plague 
seemingly limited to risk groups of homosexual men 
hemophiliacs and intravenous drug users 
by then the infections and cancers that could drastically 
shorten the lives of those infected with the virus had a name 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome aids 
quickly other wellknown names in the arts and public life were 
drawn into the patchwork of torn lives symbolized by an immense 
quilt spread in front of the washington monument 
just as the quilt has grown too large to be shipped around the 
country for display the roster of the dead can only be represented 
symbolically by this short list 
</TEXT>
