<TEXT>
a computerized process to sharpen blurry 
photos by breaking them into millions of pieces and reassembling 
them could be a boon not only to family albums but also to police 
who use photographs to solve crimes 
state police used a murat tekalps process when they 
investigated the death of a 7yearold boy who was struck by a 
vehicle while he was camping out on a hill behind his home the 
only evidence was a faint trace of tire marks on the boys tent 
police clarified the photographs and concluded that the boy was 
struck by his fathers pickup truck the case has not gone to 
trial but state police investigator james booth said the process 
was essential 
there are dozens of scenarios in which it could be used 
such as photographs of license plates documents and vehicles said 
gerald b richards chief of the fbis special photographic unit in 
washington if youve got one big case it works on its 
golden he said 
tekalp a university of rochester electrical engineering 
professor has only developed the process for still photographs 
but he said moving pictures are his next subject the computer 
process uses a highresolution scanner to divide a negative into 
more than 2 million pixels calculations then are made about what 
caused the blur the computer sorts the information and produces a 
clearer image and then a new negative is made 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
nitric and sulfuric acids in rain are 
killing mountain forests in the east by damaging the foliage 
crippling photosynthesis and by upsetting trees nutritional 
balance a researcher says 
this finding is a surprise because sulfuric acid from acid 
rain was shown in previous studies to be harmless to crop plants 
said jay s jacobson who based his findings on five years of field 
and greenhouse experiments 
we have demonstrated that sulfuric acid at concentrations 
similar to those found in acidic mist and cloudwater seriously 
weakens the foliage thus impairing the trees photosynthetic 
process at high concentrations it kills the needles outright 
said jacobson a plant physiologist at cornell universitys boyce 
thompson institute for plant research 
while sulfuric acid destroyed the foliage nitric acid a form 
of nitrogen fertilizer upset the trees balance of nutrients he 
said all plants need nutrients from the soil to grow if we give 
them too much of one nutrient such as nitrogen fertilizer from the 
atmosphere and not enough of others the trees would develop chronic 
nutritional deficiencies a factor detrimental to the health of the 
affected tree in the long run 
scientists have long suspected that acid precipitation has been 
the cause of mountain forest decline red spruce which grow at 
high elevations across the northeast are important for the pulp 
and paper industries 
sulfuric acid is formed in the atmosphere when sulfur oxides 
from the combustion of coal and oil undergo chemical reactions 
nitric acid is produced by internal combustion engines and from the 
combustion of oil and coal 
jacobsons findings will be published next year in the canadian 
journal of forest research the water air and soil pollution 
journal and physiologia plantarum in sweden 
</TEXT>
