<TEXT>
the united states spent nearly 6 billion from 
august through october to stem the dollars rise and keep the 
currency in the trading range set with other major industrialized 
nations the federal reserve reported 
the quarterly foreignexchange report released wednesday by the 
federal reserve bank of new york showed the fed and the treasury 
sold 5871 billion in exchange for west german marks and japanese 
yen during the three months ended oct 31 
the new york fed said the government sold a total of 3289 
billion for japanese yen and 2582 billion for west german marks 
the move the governments secondlargest unloading of dollars 
ever in a threemonth period comes on the heels of the 
recordsetting sale of 1192 billion in the quarter ended july 31 
the dollar initially got a boost during the augustoctober 
quarter from a spate of favorable economic data because of the 
figures which indicated the economy was not as sluggish as 
previously believed the federal reserve was not inclined to push 
interest rates lower which kept returns relatively attractive on 
dollardenominated securities 
gains in retail sales and employment and a betterthanexpected 
trade report helped boost the dollar to its high during the period 
of 200 west german marks and 14898 japanese yen on sept 15 
but a meeting of the group of seven industrial nations in 
washington later that month produced a sharply worded statement 
criticizing the dollars rise the group which includes the 
united states britain west germany japan canada italy and 
france favors a relatively weaker dollar which is seen as 
helping reduce the huge us trade deficit 
the group of seven called the dollars rise inconsistent with 
longrun fundamentals and said a further rise could adversely 
affect prospects for the world economy 
the bulk of the feds intervention which was coordinated with 
other leading central banks occurred in the weeks leading up to 
the g7 meeting and in several weeks following the gathering 
activities after the g7 meeting were forceful said sam 
y cross a new york fed executive vice president who presented the 
report to reporters we did act quite forcefully to reinforce the 
policy statement of the group 
since that time the dollar has trended downward cross said 
by early october the dollar had plunged to 18650 west german 
marks and 13860 japanese yen 
by midoctober the upward pressure on the dollar had fully 
eased interest rates in europe and in japan traditionally far 
lower than us rates were higher thereby shrinking the 
advantage the united states had in terms of return to investors and 
reducing demand for dollars 
furthermore more recent reports indicated sluggishness in the 
us economy that raised speculation the federal reserve might ease 
credit to help prevent a recession 
the spotlight shifted to foreign currencies particularly the 
mark which was bolstered by west germanys bright economic 
prospects and the beginnings of a massive reform movement in 
eastern europe 
the dollar now is trading at about 176177 marks and 143144 
yen 
currency traders are often keenly aware of the activities of 
central banks in the open markets but the feds policy is to 
comment only well after the fact the fed does not provide any data 
on intervention by foreign central banks 
