the federal exportimport bank says it is 
willing to protect private banks against political violence and 
other risks in countries where they make loans to support purchases 
of us goods 
the bank did not specify any countries in its announcement 
wednesday the new guarantee could be given to lenders to the 
soviet union and other east european countries if as many business 
people hope laws are repealed that limit us aid to those nations 
in the past the bank required the borrowing government to make 
a guarantee against financial loss from violence and foreign 
government actions when the money was lent over five years or more 
for a government purchase private projects required a guarantee 
from a private bank in the borrowing country on loans made for 
less than five years the exportimport bank has sometimes covered 
political risks 
on tuesday the bank told its advisory committee that there have 
been several requests that it take over the longterm political 
guarantee john d macomber the banks president said he expected 
there will be many more such requests in the future 
ann frey a press officer at the bank explained that this was 
because projects in some countries that had been delayed by 
international debt problems are now being brought up again foreign 
governments are unwilling to take on the risk of additional debt 
themselves she suggested 
she said requests for the new us guarantees have come from 
turkey and some latin american countries 
an exportimport bank guarantee often makes the difference in 
closing a deal other governments of industrial countries 
especially france and japan compete vigorously for international 
orders 
political risks include war rebellion confiscation 
nationalization and the refusal of a foreign government to allow 
payments to leave its country the bank said the new longterm 
guarantees will be available after the us government and the 
borrowing government have made an agreement that provides a way to 
settle disputes 
the us governments overseas private investment corporation 
already offers similar insurance to americans who make direct 
investments not loans in other countries some governments 
especially in latin america have been reluctant to make agreements 
on dispute settlement because they are unwilling to see trade 
disputes handled anywhere but in their own courts 
