<DOCNO> AP891207-0219 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission said it 
is ready to prosecute market manipulation by the practice of short 
selling but the evidence isnt always there 
were committed to identify short selling abuse wherever it 
may occur said john sturc of the secs enforcement division 
told a house panel wednesday 
but he and another sec official also told a subcommittee of the 
house committee on governmental affairs short selling also 
provides the market with two vital benefits 
richard g ketchum head of the secs division of market 
regulation told the panel those benefits are market liquidity and 
price efficiency which help prevent volatility the steep price 
rises and drops that can panic investors and send the market 
plunging 
but sturc an associate director of the enforcement division 
noted that he and ketchum were not here to defend or attack short 
selling 
in shortselling an investor tries to take advantage of an 
anticipated drop in the price of a companys stock the investor 
borrows stock from a broker and sells it hoping to replace it with 
stock purchased at a lower price the investors profit would come 
from the difference between the price obtained for the borrowed 
stock and the lower price paid to replace it 
short selling is not illegal and stockholders are allowed to 
lend or borrow stock they are holding for customers if the stock 
has been purchased on margin the buyer did not put up the full 
purchase price 
but in testimony last week before the commerce consumer and 
monetary affairs subcommittee some witnesses complained some 
professional shortsellers often break the rules to get a stock to 
drop quickly and spread false rumors about a company its products 
or its management 
that testimony was about the overthecounter market which does 
not have the same rules governing short sales as do the stock 
exchanges the national association of securities dealers a 
private selfregulating group oversees the overthecounter market 
sturc however noted that the sec considers all complaints of 
short selling abuses but often investigations do not lead to 
sustainable evidence of violations of the antifraud provisions of 
the federal securities laws 
at the beginning of the hearing the subcommittee chairman rep 
doug barnard jr dga said he was not sure that the sec is on 
the same wavelength as the subcommittee 
but sturc explained that often when companies complain they are 
the victims of short sellers spreading false rumors there is no 
proof where the rumors originated or whether it has had an effect 
of the companys stock 
we have a strong enforcement interest said sturc adding 
i regret to say mr chairman we have not received allegations 
of misconduct to quite the degree of specificity as has been 
presented to the subcommittee by several of the witnesses we would 
be happy to receive them my job is to try find violators and catch 
them and thats what i like to do 
after the session barnard told reporters that the hearings were 
not a witchhunt as far as the sec or nasd were concerned i 
thought there was good explanations 
</TEXT>
