<TEXT>
west germany today awarded a 
license to build and operate a private mobile telephone system that 
analysts estimate could be worth more than 5 billion to a 
fournation consortium 
led by mannesmann ag the group also includes pacific telesis 
group of the united states cable and wireless plc of britain 
lyonnaise des eaux of france and deutsche genossenschaftsbank a 
major west german bank 
the post ministry chose the consortium from a large field of 
contending groups which included several of west germanys largest 
companies and international telecommunications concerns 
the private network called d2 will compete with the post 
ministrys own d1 system it will be the second digital cellular 
system in west germany the german government now operates an 
analog cellular network and plans to build its own digital system 
mannesmann kienzle gmbh the electronics subsidiary of the west 
german engineering concern will hold a majority stake in the 
consortium called mannesmann mobilfunk gmbh 
analysts have said that operating a mobile phone network in 
denselypopulated west germany will be an extremely profitable 
business in the 1990s the value of the license has been estimated 
at 2 billion to 10 billion marks or the equivalent of about 11 
billion to 56 billion 
mannesmann has said construction of the network will require 
initial investments of 22 billion 
rumors that the consortium won the bidding war spurred a rally 
in mannesmann stock in recent days since last thursday mannesmann 
stock has surged some 25 percent to close at 34000 marks a share 
or about 192 on wednesday 
the decision by post minister christian schwarzschilling was 
based on a recommendation of a special advisory panel that ranked 
the mannesmann consortium first among the bidders 
pacific telesis which holds a 26 percent interest in the 
consortium has not put a dollar value on its share of the license 
but analysts estimate it could increase the pershare value of the 
companys stock by 3 or 4 as the financial market reacts to the 
announcement company spokeswoman amy damianakes said 
we view the cellular business as an alexander graham bell 
opportunity sam ginn pactels president and chief executive 
officer said in a news release today 
this license expands our reach into the international cellular 
market and provides significant potential for increasing shareowner 
value during the 1990s ginn said 
pacific telesis one of the baby bells created after the 
breakup of american telephone amp telegraph co has a contract with 
the consortium to design engineer and manage the new systems 
construction pactels 26 percent interest covers about 16 million 
potential cellular subscribers compared with its nearly 30 million 
potential subscribers in the united states ginn said 
other partners in the consortium are mannesmann ag deutsche 
genossenschaftsbank cable and wireless plc lyonnaise des eaux and 
the national associations of electrical and automobile trades 
